{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01PbQaxHRR45HoXctg23bfth","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"TCP connectivity works fine. The ray-head is reachable at port 6379. So the issue is specifically with the ray.init() call starting a local raylet in the ray-client pod.\n\nThe error \"Can't find node_ip_address.json for 60 seconds\" means the raylet process started but didn't write the file. This usually happens when:\n1. The raylet crashed immediately after starting\n2. /tmp has permission issues\n3. Plasma store failed to start\n\nLet me try to get more verbose logging from ray to understand what's happening. Let me also check if the ray version in the client pod is the same (2.9.0).\nWhen I call ray.init() with the ray-head address, Ray needs to create the session directory, start the plasma store and raylet, then have the raylet connect back to the GCS. If either the plasma store or raylet crashes during startup, that node_ip_address.json file never gets written. Let me dig into Ray's internal logs to see what's actually failing, or try using `ray start --address` directly in the pod to get clearer error messages. The issue might be that `/tmp` in the pod has size constraints or the raylet needs extra capabilities for shared memory. Let me try running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` directly in the ray-client pod to see if that works, since that's essentially what `ray.init()` does internally.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":262,"cache_read_input_tokens":40779,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":262},"output_tokens":35,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5492027-9e24-4f6a-adc0-2a43726cf418","uuid":"492effd9-7afa-4019-8555-c4897d37ac4c","req