{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015QpmeHxHrbY9vyMCwpDfy7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"`ray start --address=ray-head:6379` works fine in the ray-client pod! It says \"Ray runtime started.\" So the issue is specific to `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` being called in an exec context.\n\nWait, but `ray start` is a separate process that runs in the background. Then when we exit, it stays running. So the issue with `ray.init()` is that it's an in-process call that needs to work.\n\nThe difference between `ray start` (the CLI) and `ray.init(address=...)` (Python API) is:\n- `ray start` launches the raylet and plasma_store as background processes and returns immediately\n- `ray.init(address=...)` also starts local processes but then waits for them to register with the GCS\n\nSo `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` completes successfully in 2 seconds, but `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` times out after 60 seconds looking for the node_ip_address.json file. The CLI command and Python API seem to handle the connection differently in Ray 2.x.\n\nThe error message is coming from the node startup code, which expects the raylet to write that JSON file once it's running. The question is whether Ray is still actually running in the pod after `ray start` completes, and if so, whether `ray.init()` should be able to connect to it instead of trying to start new processes.\n\nBut the validation command requires connecting to `ray-head:6379` specifically, so I need to understand what's different between running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` (which succeeds) and then calling `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` from Python (which fails). When you provide an address to `ray.init()`, it should connect to that existing cluster, but it might also be trying to start local components that are conflicting with the setup. Maybe I should check the ray session logs directly in the pod to see what's actually happening. Or I could try stopping any existing ray instance first, then attempt `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` again with more verbose logging to catch what's failing. The fact that `ray start` succeeds but the same address fails with `ray.init()` suggests something subtle is going wrong during initialization.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1308,"cache_read_input_tokens":41041,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1308},"output_tokens":37,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5492027-9e24-4f6a-adc0-2a43726cf418","uuid":"53bcded7-b4ca-4940-9292-49157f117cab","request_id":"req_011Cc4AkSWtMFJTDroLMxfsW"}
