{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01GGCBNKuCS21K5BfhiAKCgR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The dashboard agent logs don't show an error. Let me check the agent error logs more specifically. But what's interesting is the dashboard agent says `process_watcher.py:66 -- check_parent_via_pipe` - this checks if the parent (raylet) is still alive via a pipe. If the raylet dies, the agent exits.\n\nWait, looking at the timeline again:\n- `ray start` ran at 18:24:09 and said \"Ray runtime started\"\n- The dashboard_agent at timestamp 18:24:13 is from the FIRST `ray start` run (the agent started by the first successful `ray start`)\n- The second raylet at PID 297 started at 18:24:17\n\nSo when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` was called at 18:24:17, the first raylet was still running from 18:24:09. This means `ray.init()` must have started a second raylet instead of connecting to the existing one - which suggests the first raylet had already crashed or stopped responding by that point.\n\nLooking at the log files more carefully, raylet.out shows PID 103 from the first `ray start` at 18:21:38, while raylet.1.out shows PID 297 from 18:24:17. The raylet started by my second `ray start` at 18:24:09 isn't appearing in either log file, which means it likely crashed immediately after starting. agent crashes with exit code -1 immediately. Looking at the dashboard_agent.log, the agent was initializing properly at 18:24:13, but when the raylet started at 18:24:17, it was a different instance than the one that spawned the agent. I think when I ran `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, the Python process connected to an existing local raylet through the session rather than the one created by the second `ray start` command.\n\nThe socket directory shows `plasma_store` and `plasma_store.1` but no `raylet` socket from either start attempt. The first `ray start` did succeed and ran for about 30 minutes before