{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01S9kEkY6kWtgCS4tQN9dsFm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Both agents started successfully and logged \"registered routes\" / \"starting runtime env agent\". But they exited with code -1 according to the raylet. The `process_watcher.py` says `check_parent_via_pipe` - it's monitoring the raylet (PID 560) via a pipe. The agents exit when they detect the raylet has died.\n\nSo the causal chain is:\n1. `ray start` starts the raylet (PID 560) + agents\n2. When `ray.init()` is called from Python, it starts PYTHON WORKER PROCESSES\n3. The Python worker processes try to connect to the raylet\n4. Something causes the raylet to crash\n5. The agents detect the raylet died (via the pipe) and exit with code -1\n\nOr maybe the agents fail first and that triggers the raylet to die. Let me check the `python-core-driver` log from the latest run to see what the Python worker is doing and whether it's killing something. Looking at the timeline in `raylet.out`, the dashboard agent exited with code -1 at 18:26:52, but I need to see what happened right before that.\n\nThe agents died at the exact moment `ray.init()` was called, not before. The first successful run had agents at PID 161, but the second run had agents with identifier 1774710931. The raylet message says it exited because that agent failed, and the dashboard agent log shows it was running fine at 18:26:38 when routes registered, then exited at 18:26:52 when `ray.init()` ran. Since `process_watcher.py` monitors the raylet through a pipe and exits the agent if the raylet dies, the sequence must be that the raylet crashes first, triggering the agent to exit.\n\nThe worker process tries to connect to the raylet socket at `/tmp/ray/session_latest/sockets/raylet`, and the error \"Unable to register worker with raylet. No such file or directory\" suggests the socket file isn't found. But the socket should exist after `ray start` completes. I'm wondering if `ray start` actually creates the raylet socket reliably, and whether it persists until `ray.init()` is called—this might be a timing issue.\n\nWhen `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` runs, it seems to start a second raylet process in the same session, which conflicts with the first one from `ray start` and causes it to crash. The socket then disappears, and when `ray.init` tries to connect to the original raylet, it can't find it. Looking at the logs, the first raylet from `ray start` appears to have crashed on its own between the two commands, which is the real mystery I need to investigate.\n\nThe first raylet ran fine for 30 seconds after `ray start`, but when I ran a fresh `ray start` at 18:26:34, the raylet crashed almost immediately at 18:26:52—which is exactly when `ray.init()` was called. It seems like the Python worker connecting to the raylet is what's causing the crash.\n\nLet me check the `core-driver` log to understand what's happening during that connection.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2626,"cache_read_input_tokens":77464,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2626},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5492027-9e24-4f6a-adc0-2a43726cf418","uuid":"137d2d03-3f58-4dc7-bbec-948ac309e59f","request_id":"req_011Cc4BEivtdCjYVTdSmAT8a"}
