{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015YgUti6B4LNqnfjk1vAXD1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The raylet says the agent failed. But from the dashboard_agent.log, the agent appeared to start up fine (registered routes, found raylet PID 560, checked parent via pipe). So what killed the agent?\n\nThe process_watcher.py uses `check_parent_via_pipe` - it monitors the raylet. But maybe after 18:26:38 (last agent log entry), the raylet crashed for some reason, and the agent exited at 18:26:52 due to detecting the raylet was gone.\n\nBut the raylet's own log (raylet.out) says it crashed BECAUSE the agents exited. This is a chicken-and-egg situation. \n\nLooking at the timeline more carefully: the raylet detected the agent exiting at 18:26:52 with exit code -1, then immediately shut itself down. So the agent definitely exited first, but the dashboard_agent.log just stops at 18:26:38 without any error message explaining why.\n\nThere's a 14-second gap between the last log entry and the actual exit, and that's exactly when `ray.init()` was running. The agent was likely checking the raylet via a pipe in `process_watcher.py`, and if the raylet died or the pipe broke, the agent would exit. But the raylet's logs suggest it was still alive at 18:26:52 when it detected the agent failure—so either the raylet crashed silently in those 14 seconds, or something else caused the agent process to terminate. So either the raylet crashed silently and broke the pipe, causing both agents to exit, or one agent died first and triggered the raylet shutdown, which then broke the pipe for the other agent. The key question is whether the agent_manager thread can still log messages after the main raylet process crashes, or if there's a signal handler writing that shutdown message.\n\nNow I'm wondering if this is actually an out-of-memory issue—the kernel's OOM killer could be terminating the agents. Looking at the timeline, the first `ray start` at 18:21:38 completed successfully and ran for 30 seconds, but every subsequent attempt crashes around 18:26:52 when `ray.init()` gets called. The difference is that the first run didn't spawn a Python worker process, while the later runs do. That worker process could be consuming too much memory and triggering the OOM killer, which would then take down the agents and raylet along with it. The log_monitor from the previous session is still running and connected to the same GCS instance, reading from the same session directory. This could be causing conflicts when the new raylet starts and registers with GCS—the old log_monitor might be interfering with the new one's initialization. The first `ray start` worked because it had a clean slate without any lingering processes from a prior session. the pkill at 18:26:25 should have killed everything ray-related, but it's unclear if it fully completed since the shell exited with code 137. Looking at the ps output afterward, only the log_monitor from the third start (PID 561) is visible. So the pattern seems to be that log_monitor processes survive the `ray stop` command and persist across sessions, potentially interfering with new raylet startups. I should do a clean kill of all log_monitor processes and then attempt a fresh start to test this hypothesis. I'm going to try a more direct approach: kill the stale log_monitor process by its PID, clear out the /tmp/ray directory completely, and start fresh. I'm also wondering if I should look back at the raylet error logs from that first crash to understand what actually went wrong there.\n\nSince those logs got deleted when I cleaned up /tmp/ray, I'll need to just proceed with the cleanup. My suspicion is that the log_monitor is still connected to the GCS with the old cluster ID from the first run, and when a new raylet tries to register with the same node ID, the GCS rejects it or there's some conflict happening.\n\nThe safest approach is to kill the log_monitor by its PID, terminate any remaining ray processes, wipe /tmp/ray, then start fresh with `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` and let it stabilize before calling `ray.init()`.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":885,"cache_read_input_tokens":81618,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":885},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5492027-9e24-4f6a-adc0-2a43726cf418","uuid":"ce5a2fab-5582-428a-b9d3-e5f90fe92826","request_id":"req_011Cc4BHccDRMgjxZujjDJgK"}
