{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WkQ5F9ks1LfKqMnjadK3Kc","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the raylet log at 18:30:14:\n1. `agent_manager.cc:84: The raylet exited immediately because one Ray agent failed` (threads 914 and 916)\n2. `raylet_util.h:28: Sending SIGTERM` (threads 914 and 916) \n3. `worker_pool.cc:498: Started worker process with pid 1021-1030` (thread 855 - the main raylet thread!)\n4. `main.cc:372: Raylet received SIGTERM, shutting down...` (thread 855)\n\nThe key insight here is a race condition: the agent manager threads detected the agents failed and initiated shutdown via SIGTERM, but simultaneously the main raylet thread was spinning up pre-warmed Python workers because the driver had successfully connected. So the driver did establish a connection and the raylet began preparing resources, but then the raylet terminated itself due to the agent failure happening at the exact same moment.\n\nNow I need to figure out why the agents died in the first place. Both the dashboard_agent and runtime_env_agent exited at 18:30:14, about 29 seconds after the dashboard_agent's last log entry at 18:29:45. There's a circular dependency issue here: the agent monitors the raylet's health via a pipe in `process_watcher.py`, so if the raylet dies the agent should die too. But the logs suggest the agent died first, causing the raylet to shut itself down. The question is whether the raylet actually closed the pipe or if something else caused the agent process to exit.\n\nThe more likely scenario is that the agents were killed externally—possibly by the OOM killer. When `ray.init()` spawns 10 pre-warmed Python worker processes, each consuming around 80MB of RAM, that's 800MB just for workers. Combined with the raylet, log_monitor, dashboard_agent, and runtime_env_agent, the pod might have hit its memory limit and the kernel started terminating processes. I should check the system