{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01CEs1uJED95tmwdKJo8b1ti","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see clearly: between 18:29:43 and 18:30:14, NOTHING happened in the raylet. The raylet just received notifications of 7 nodes (some alive, some not), and then at 18:30:14 the agents suddenly died.\n\nThe agents started at 18:29:43 and died at 18:30:14. That's exactly 31 seconds later. And the PREVIOUS run had agents starting at 18:26:38 and dying at 18:26:52, which is only 14 seconds. \n\nBut what's consistent: the agents die exactly when `ray.init()` is called. Let me check what the dashboard_agent does during `ray.init()`:\nWhen the driver calls `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, it connects to GCS, locates the local session with the raylet, and initializes a worker that spawns a gRPC client to communicate with the raylet. The raylet then starts pre-warming workers, but at that exact moment the agents crash. The agent logs show it was registering routes right before dying at 18:30:14, so something about the worker initialization or pre-warming process is killing it.\n\nThe agent monitors the raylet through a pipe via `process_watcher.py`, and if the raylet closes its write end, the agent exits. But I'm noticing something in the raylet logs—there are node alive/dead notifications being received around the same time the agents die, which suggests the raylet might be detecting node state changes that trigger something catastrophic. The GCS is tracking 7 nodes total—4 alive nodes including the current ray-client and 2 workers, plus 3 dead nodes from previous sessions. I'm wondering if the dashboard_agent connecting to the head's dashboard at port 41235 could be the issue, maybe the head is rejecting multiple connections from the same client IP, but that doesn't make sense since the agent is initiating the connection to the head, not the other way around. Let me dig deeper into the `check_parent_via_pipe` logic.\n\nIn Ray 2.9.0, the raylet passes a file descriptor to agents that they monitor to detect when the raylet shuts down—when the raylet closes its end of the pipe during shutdown, the agents exit. But the real question is what's triggering the raylet to shut down in the first place. I'm shifting perspective here: what if the problem is actually with the `--listen-port=52365` that the dashboard_agent is using?\n\nIf that port is still occupied by a previous agent instance that wasn't properly terminated, the new agent won't be able to bind to it and will fail to start. Let me check whether port 52365 is currently in use.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2452,"cache_read_input_tokens":95605,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2452},"output_tokens":29,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d5492027-9e24-4f6a-adc0-2a43726cf418","uuid":"375e0864-23b4-4201-9802-7b556581ebb2","request_id":"req_011Cc4BWe1ujogdhfGbK5beD"}
